messages.content: Why not using mixtral directly?

TLDR: Tokens per second and optimizations. 
We need to speed up the network at this point, not slow it down. The VLLM piece is going to enable us to accelerate the network by means of batched inference. Then we will be able to take a potential hit in tokens/second, but not sooner. These miners are sitting around bored 🙂
Exciting! How will the current economies of scale be impacted? How will this disturb/disincentivize the existing "whales" with tons of hotkeys running the same models?
Was wondering the same thing.

Here's the gist of it. Right now miners are only actively serving validator requests around 5% of the time. This means you can run ~20 hotkeys on a single LLM (crude math but this is the idea). As a result, large cabals will typically have, say a hundred keys with only 5 LLMs under the hood. This means that their cost per hotkey is 1/20th that of miners who are running 1-to-1. Of course it takes some skill to setup systems such as this but people have been doing it since the dark ages. What the new changes will do is increase the utilization of miners to be much greater than 5% (say 50-75%) so that there is no way to 'reuse' an underlying LLM.

This sweeps a fair bit of stuff under the rug.. e.g. miner cost may be dominated by registration in which case the cost to inference isn't as important.

The batched inference will also mean we can query much smaller groups of uids per forward pass. Let's say we use batch size 10 and we still query 50 uids. Those 10 different prompts will be sharded across the 50 and so effectively only 5 uids in the network will receive the same request. This will make repetition a negligible effect because you'll need to have  20% of the network to have any chance of seeing the same prompt twice. Thus no repitition. Of course, we can use batch size = sample size so that all uids get unique prompts every time -> zero repetition. This is possible because batch processing of NNs is insanely efficient.
